To find all real numbers $x$ such that the product $(x + i)((x + 1) + i)((x + 2) + i)$ is pure imaginary, we start by expanding the given expression step by step:

First, expand the first two factors:
\begin{align*}
(x + i)((x + 1) + i) &= x(x + 1) + xi + (x + 1)i + i^2 \\
&= x^2 + x + xi + (x + 1)i - 1 \\
&= x^2 + x - 1 + (x + x + 1)i \\
&= x^2 + x - 1 + (2x + 1)i.
\end{align*}

Next, multiply this result by the third factor:
\begin{align*}
(x^2 + x - 1 + (2x + 1)i)((x + 2) + i) &= (x^2 + x - 1)(x + 2) + (x^2 + x - 1)i + (2x + 1)(x + 2)i + (2x + 1)i^2 \\
&= x^3 + 2x^2 + x^2 + 2x - x - 2 + (x^2 + x - 1)i + (2x^2 + 4x + 2x + 4)i - (2x + 1) \\
&= x^3 + 3x^2 - x - 3 + (3x^2 + 6x + 1)i.
\end{align*}

For the product to be pure imaginary, the real part must be zero. Therefore, we set the real part equal to zero and solve for $x$:
\begin{align*}
x^3 + 3x^2 - x - 3 &= 0 \\
(x + 3)(x + 1)(x - 1) &= 0.
\end{align*}

This equation gives us three solutions for $x$: $-3$, $-1$, and $1$. Therefore, the real numbers $x$ that make the product pure imaginary are $\boxed{-3, -1, 1}$.

